				</div>
<div class="brdr20 lowlighted" id="tie-lb-20250508174403" data-timeframe="20250508174403"><div class="comment-body-live " id="lb-1011770"><div class="Perennial under-performers in the IPL, Punjab Kings (previously Kings XI Punjab) have looked like the real deal this season under new captain Shreyas Iyer and coach Ricky Ponting.&amp;nbsp;\nThe team has a strong Indian presence with Iyer complemented by the likes of Priyansh Arya, Prabhsimran Singh, Shashank Singh, Nehal Wadhera, Yuzvendra Chahal and Arshdeep Singh.&amp;nbsp;\nFormer India cricketer-turned-analyst Ajay Jadeja, talking on JioHotstar after PBKS' victory over LSG in their previous IPL game,&amp;nbsp; highlighted how Punjab Kings' long-term investment in their Indian core is finally paying off.&amp;nbsp;\n&amp;ldquo;The key for Punjab Kings has been their Indian core. They've invested in players like Prabhsimran Singh for years&amp;mdash;even back when Anil [Kumble] was involved. They waited patiently to see him deliver, and now he&amp;rsquo;s started scoring runs consistently. Shreyas Iyer, the captain, has also been phenomenal. He&amp;rsquo;s had a few low scores, but when he gets going, he takes the team to a commanding position,&quot; Jadeja said.&amp;nbsp;\nHe went on to add: &quot;Over the years, the team had a strong Australian presence&amp;mdash;probably something the owners preferred&amp;mdash;but this season, it&amp;rsquo;s the Indian players who are making the real impact. There&amp;rsquo;s a belief in the group from the very first game. They&amp;rsquo;ve played as a unit, without relying on just big names. Everyone&amp;rsquo;s contributing in their own way, and that&amp;rsquo;s been the biggest strength of this side.&amp;rdquo;" id="lbcontentbody"></div><div class="lvblg-box-shr">
							<div class="ieo-datetime">
								<span>17:44 (IST)</span><span>08 May 2025</span></div>
